fields.content: My first review of this course
My second review of this course
The subject of elliptic curves encompasses a vast amount of mathematics. Our aim in this section is to summarize just enough of the basic theory for cryptographic applications.

In the previous section we developed the theory of elliptic curves geometrically. For example, the sum of two distinct points P and Q on an elliptic curve E is defined by drawing the line L connecting P to Q and then finding the third point where L and E intersect. However, in order to apply the theory of elliptic curves to cryptography, we need to look at elliptic curves whose points have coordinates in a finite field Fp.

Let E be an elliptic curve over the finite field Fp and let P and Q be points in E(Fp). The Elliptic Curve Discrete Logarithm Problem (ECDLP) is the problem of finding an integer n such that Q = nP. By analogy with the discrete logarithm problem for F* p, we denote this integer n by n = logP (Q).
fields.description: The elliptic curve discrete logarithm problem

fields.content: The Elliptic Curve Digital Signature Algorithm (ECDSA), which is described in the digital signatures module, is a straightforward analogue of the digital signature algorithm (DSA).

fields.content: For students unfamiliar with the theory of groups, we briefly introduce a few basic concepts that should help to place the study of discrete logarithms into a broader context.
fields.description: An overview of the theory of groups

fields.content: In this section we introduce the student to Lenstra's elliptic curve factorization algorithm. It is the third fastest classical algorithm of its kind.
Computers speak binary, so they are especially well suited to doing calculations modulo 2. This suggests that it might be more efficient to use elliptic curves modulo 2.
fields.description: Elliptic curves over F2 and F2K

fields.content: There are many applications of the Weil pairing in which it is necessary to work in fields Fpk of prime power order. In this section we discuss the m-embedding degree, which is the smallest value of k such that E(Fpk )[m] is as large as possible, and we give an application called the MOV algorithm that reduces the ECDLP in E(Fp) to the DLP in F* pk . We then describe distortion maps on E and use them to define a modified Weil pairing ^em for which ^em(P, P) is nontrivial.
fields.description: The Weil Pairing over fields of prime power order
